    "body": "@PascalPrecht didn't get the chance to run and test it. However, after digging into the code, the first thing I would suspect is the fact that the model used in `StatusListPicker` (from the `LanguageView` component) is not `CurrencyStore.currenciesModel` but [](https://github.com/status-im/StatusQ/blob/69b5cb1988bc86cf4a6d21ef693de71c38bce060/src/StatusQ/Components/StatusListPicker.qml#L285) the internal `d.filteredModel` which is constructed in [`init`](https://github.com/status-im/StatusQ/blob/69b5cb1988bc86cf4a6d21ef693de71c38bce060/src/StatusQ/Components/StatusListPicker.qml#L164) and [`applyFilter`](https://github.com/status-im/StatusQ/blob/69b5cb1988bc86cf4a6d21ef693de71c38bce060/src/StatusQ/Components/StatusListPicker.qml#L185).\r\n\r\nAlso considering that documentation says \"Warning: The returned object is not guaranteed to remain valid. It should not be used in [property bindings](https://doc.qt.io/qt-5/qtqml-syntax-propertybinding.html).\" (see [`ListModel.get()`](https://doc.qt.io/qt-5/qml-qtqml-models-listmodel.html#get-method)) I would assume that the object we change `selected` might not be the same instance as the one in the original `ListModel`. A quick workaround I see for this peculiar implementation is to emit a signal from `CurrencyModel` that the model was updated and connect it to `applyFilter` \"slot\".\r\n\r\n-----\r\n\r\nAfter looking into the implementation the following improvements come into my mind:\r\n- Keeping selected element state in the model generates issues. The usual approach is to have a single source of truth and avoid syncing multiple sources as it is done now. That means an improvement and a better fix might be to remove the `selected` role from the `ListItem` in the `CurrenciesStore` model and replace it with usage of the `CurrenciesStore.currentCurrency`. That will require transforming [this line](https://github.com/status-im/StatusQ/blob/69b5cb1988bc86cf4a6d21ef693de71c38bce060/src/StatusQ/Components/StatusListPicker.qml#L332) into `selected: model.key === CurrenciesStore.currentCurrency`. This way we can remove the `updateCurrenciesModel` call and keep one source of truth.\r\n- Another source of issues is the  `property string currentCurrency: walletSection.currentCurrency` entry in the `CurrenciesStore`. This binding is ephemeral, when you execute the above button snippet `root.currencyStore.currentCurrency = \"eur\"` breaks the binding creating a divergence from `walletSection.currentCurrency`. Therefore a change in `walletSection.currentCurrency` won't be reflected anymore, unless you have another sync back mechanism. A good improvement will be to make this binding readonly and add a function to change it. Another will be to have a two way binding.\r\n- Also the manual model filtering transfer is a maintenance burden. The usual C++ way is to build a proxy model, not sure if this can be easily done in NIM, but it is a more efficient way. Otherwise every change you do in the model you have to propagate it to delegates, as mentioned above",
